<br>
Not so long ago, I did a break down of the dmg/sec different classes could do with the combinations of PBAoE spells they had available to them at various levels.  I'll see if I can dig that out for you guys...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> EDIT</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Found the post.  Here's a clip from it:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I finally took the time to sit down and look closely at the spell info for wizard AoE's and mage AoE's.<br>
<br>
Sarivek, when you say the &quot;recast delay&quot; you are actually talking about &quot;spell recovery time&quot; which is the amount of time before you can cast a different spell. According to the spdat file, the cast time on wizard PB AoE's is 2 seconds, and the spell recovery time 2.25 seconds. What this means is 2.25 seconds after your spell hits, you can cast a different spell. The actual recast recovery time on your AoE's is 6.0 seconds... meaning it would be another 6.0 seconds before you could recast the same spell. (Btw, I don't know where the 1 second recast time came from unless spdat doesn't match up to what really happens ingame.)<br>
<br>
So, this is what I was looking for: (wizzie PB AoE's are as follows)<br>
<br>
Jyll's Static Pulse (lvl 53)<br>
495 dmg / 285 mana<br>
cast time 2.0<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
recast recovery 6.0<br>
<br>
Jyll's Zypher of Ice (lvl 56)<br>
594 dmg / 314 mana<br>
cast time 2.0<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
recast recovery 6.0<br>
<br>
Jyll's Wave of Heat (lvl 59)<br>
638-648 dmg / 342 mana<br>
cast time 2.0<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
recast recovery 6.0<br>
<br>
So, using these cast times and spell recovery times, a wizard spends 4.25 seconds on each casting of an AoE when going down the chain of these 3 spells. At lvl 60 a wizzard chaining a round of these AoE spells will look like this:<br>
<br>
cast time of 2.0<br>
hit targets for 495 dmg (285 mana)<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
cast time 2.0<br>
hit targets for 594 dmg (314 mana)<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
cast time 2.0<br>
hit targets for 648 dmg (342 mana)<br>
spell recovery 2.25<br>
<br>
Total damage/time/mana cost = 1737dmg/12.75seconds/941mana<br>
<br>
This averages out to 136 dmg per second.. to each mob who is hit... something to be very proud of!  <br>
<br>
Now, gonna make you feel so very powerful and proud to be a wizard (not that you already aren't or shouldn't be)  <br>
<br>
Mage PB AoE is this:<br>
<br>
Scintillation (lvl 51)<br>
597-607 dmg / 361 mana<br>
cast time 3.0<br>
spell recovery 2.5<br>
recast recovery 6.5<br>
<br>
The stats of the mage PB AoE are very close to wizzie ones, but the draw back is we only get ONE that is Point Blank. Our others aren't PB. We have the bonus of doing more damage with a single spell at a lower level, but we lose out in the long run because we don't get anymore PB AoE's.<br>
<br>
At level 53, a mage trying to chain cast this single PB AoE would be spending 9.5 seconds on each cast (start to finish). This averages 64 dmg per second.<br>
<br>
At level 53, a wizard would spend 8 seconds on each cast (start to finish using only the lvl 53 PB AoE). This averages out to 62 dmg per second.<br>
<br>
The figures for the wizard to do not take into account the clicky staff they get with the instant AE.<br>
<br>
Druid PB AoE is as follows:<br>
<br>
Upheaval (lvl 51)<br>
648-718 dmg / 625 mana<br>
casting time 5.0<br>
spell recovery 2.5<br>
recast recovery 24.0<br>
<br>
Since this is the only PB AoE for druids 50+ (that I saw when quickly breezing through them), there chaining of this spell would result in this:<br>
<br>
cast time 5.0<br>
hit targets for 718 (max which would be at lvl 58 )<br>
recast recovery time 24.0<br>
<br>
A lvl 58 druid would spend 29.0 seconds with each cast of this spell. 718/24= an average of 30dmg per second for a lvl 58 druid. Unfortunately, it ain't looking so hot for druids to do AE grouping.. not with wizzies puting out 130-180+ dmg per second, and mages falling in at 2nd place with 60+ dmg per second.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Fact is, not many classes are cut out for AoE groups.  If an AE group was short a cleric, they could settle for a shaman/druid.  If they were short a bard, they could settle for some other class.  Ultimately, the aim is to have the biggest, fastest fire power with the least downtime possible... hence the cleric/enc/bard/wiz/wiz/wiz combo that is the most powerful of them all..<br>
<br>
